apology by appellant. the respondents had sought and obtained interlocutory relief restraining the appellant from marketing certain cricket helmets. the appellant had appealed against the granting of the interlocutory relief and, although no stay of those orders was sought or granted, the appellant was informed by its former solicitor that the effect of the appeal was to operate as a stay of the interlocutory orders. acting on this advice the appellant continued to market its cricket helmets in breach of the interlocutory orders. proceedings for contempt of court were then instituted against the appellant. at the hearing of the contempt proceedings the appellant's former solicitor failed to produce all relevant facts fully and properly before the learned trial judge and accordingly the appellant was adjudged to have committed a serious contempt and was fined $10,000. the appellant appealed and sought to tender fresh evidence to explain the circumstances of the contempt. the appellant also tendered an apology to the court.
